to serve as an \u003Cstrong\u003Eenergy source\u003C/strong\u003E. They are broken down into glucose, which is used in cellular respiration to produce ATP, the energy currency of the cell.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStructural component of proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - Proteins are primarily composed of amino acids, not carbohydrates\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESynthesis of fatty acids\u003C/strong\u003E - While carbohydrates can be converted into fatty acids, this is not their primary function\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransport of oxygen\u003C/strong\u003E - Oxygen transport is primarily the function of haemoglobin in red blood cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECatalysis of biochemical reactions\u003C/strong\u003E - Enzymes, which are proteins, primarily catalyse biochemical reactions\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECarbohydrates also play roles in the synthesis of nucleic acids and cell signalling, but their main role is providing energy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Carbohydrates are a primary source of energy for the body.","Carbohydrates are involved in the synthesis of nucleic acids like RNA and DNA.","Carbohydrates play a role in cell recognition and signalling as part of glycoproteins and glycolipids."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Chandel NS. Carbohydrate Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Jan 4;13(1):a040568. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040568. PMID: 33397651; PMCID: PMC7778149"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63413"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17839"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":